        "body":"<div id=\"block-525d6703e4b0081898d6ded9\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-15T17:02:41.503+01:00\">5.02pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>PS: one last line from Dublin, from Henry McDonald:</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>There was some pre-Hallowe'en ghoulish reaction to one aspect of the budget cuts from Fianna Fail, the main opposition party in Ireland.</p> <p>The party's finance spokesman Michael McGrath warned that &quot;even the dead aren't safe from this Government.&quot;</p> <p>McGrath was referring to the measure in the budget which removes the €850 burial grant for some pensioners.&nbsp;</p> </blockquote> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-525d62a0e4b0081898d6ded7\" class=\"block is-summary\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-15T16:59:33.563+01:00\">4.59pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <h2 class=\"block-title\">Closing summary, as European markets closer higher</h2> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Amid the confusion in Washington, European stock markets ended higher. Traders still think there's going to be a deal - despite the disfunctionality in Congress.</p> <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/Pawelmorski/statuses/390141750352048128\"> <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>DC update: man in suit threw rattle out of pram.</p>— Paweł Morski (@Pawelmorski) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/Pawelmorski/statuses/390141750352048128\">October 15, 2013</a></blockquote> </figure> <p>The <strong>FTSE 100</strong> finished 41 points higher at 6,549, up 0.64%, led by mining giant Rio Tinto (with Burberry bringing up the rear, down 7.6% <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/business/2013/oct/15/us-debt-ceiling-deal-hopes-push-markets-higher-live#block-525ce3ece4b0885bd26bee4a\"><strong>following CEO Angela Ahrendts' exit to join Apple</strong></a>).</p> <p>Elsewhere on the stock market, Royal Mail shares finished 14p higher at 489p, a 48% jump on the float price.</p> <p><strong>The German Dax</strong> closed at a new record high, up 0.9%, while the French <strong>CAC</strong> closed at its highest level since 2008.</p> <p><strong>And that's a good time to stop.</strong></p> <p><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/business/2013/oct/15/us-debt-ceiling-deal-hopes-push-markets-higher-live#block-525d432ee4b06d1ee571193e\"><strong>Live coverage of the Irish budget starts here</strong></a></p> <p>There's analysis of <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/business/2013/oct/15/us-debt-ceiling-deal-hopes-push-markets-higher-live#block-525d4f28e4b0081898d6dec9\"><strong>Michael Noonan's statement here</strong></a> (from Henry)...and <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/business/2013/oct/15/us-debt-ceiling-deal-hopes-push-markets-higher-live#block-525d5debe4b0a5788cef07a7\"><strong>an explanation of how pensioners and the young unemployed will be hit hard</strong></a>.</p> <p><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/business/2013/oct/15/us-debt-ceiling-deal-hopes-push-markets-higher-live#block-525d579be4b0081898d6decf\"><strong>There's a list of key points here</strong></a>.</p> <p><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/business/2013/oct/15/www.theguardian.com/world/2013/oct/15/congress-debt-deal-default-shutdown-republicans-boehner\"><strong>Stay tuned to our US liveblog for developments in Washington</strong></a>. Could there be a deal by morning?.....</p> <p>We'll find out by tomorrow. Until then, thanks, and goodnight. <strong>GW</strong></p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-525d6190e4b0570375570eb7\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-15T16:43:21.406+01:00\">4.43pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Twists and turns in Washington this afternoon, with House Republicans proposing their own solution to the debt ceiling/budget deadlock, only to see it slapped down as a &quot;partisan attempt to appease&quot; the Tea Party by the White House.</p> <p>In the last few minutes, Senate majority leaders Harry Reid just declared that the House's proposal won't get through the Senate. Clearly a deal isn't agreed -- we'll be tracking it all through the day (and night?) here:</p> <h2><a href=\"www.theguardian.com/world/2013/oct/15/congress-debt-deal-default-shutdown-republicans-boehner\"><strong> House Republicans challenge bipartisan Senate deal to avert default – live</strong></a></h2> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-525d5f40e4b0570375570eb4\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-15T16:33:57.428+01:00\">4.33pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Henry also points out that finance minister Michael Noonan hasn't bowed to pressure from Germany over Ireland's corporation tax rate: </p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>In defiance of criticism from the German SPD, Noonan told the Dail there would be no change in Ireland's relatively low corporation tax rate.</p> <p>&quot;The tax rate is settled policy. We are 100% committed to the 12.5% corporation tax rate. This will not change,&quot; he said.</p> <p>The SPD in coalition talks with Angela Merkel has demanded the next German government led by her must ask the EU to review the Republic's corporation tax rate. The Social Democrats have argued that the low rate puts Ireland at an advantage over other EU states in terms of attracting foreign direct investment.</p> </blockquote> <p>There was one significant change, though. <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/business/2013/oct/15/us-debt-ceiling-deal-hopes-push-markets-higher-live#block-525d48d1e4b0570375570ea6%20\"><strong>As I flagged up at 2.55pm</strong></a>, Noonan did promise to stop companies registered in Ireland from being 'stateless' for tax purposes.&nbsp;</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-525d5debe4b0a5788cef07a7\" class=\"block is-key-event\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-15T16:28:50.398+01:00\">4.28pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <h2 class=\"block-title\">Henry McDonald: Pensioners and young unemployed suffer</h2> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Dublin correspondent Henry McDonald flags up that this year's budget is a blow to Irish pensioners:&nbsp;</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>One in ten of all pensioners over 70 will lose their full medical card entitling them to free health care. A subsidy of €114 per year to pay pensioners' telephone bills will also be scrapped while a death grant to pay for funerals - worth €850 - will be abolished.</p> <p>The move on pensioners could be a major political gamble given that they are one sector of the population guaranteed to get out and vote in elections.</p> <p>The Finance Minister also risked alienating pensioners, who make up a large proportion of savers, over his decision to increase tax on interest gained from savings - the so called DIRT tax rate – which is to be raised to 41%.</p> <p>Those unemployed under the age of 25 would also bear the brunt of the cuts with jobseeker's allowance being slashed from the current €144 per week to €100. The age of eligibility for the full social payment of €188 (still one of the most generous in the whole of the EU) will be raised to the age of 26.</p> </blockquote> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-525d5c98e4b0667d2b3c66c5\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-15T16:23:18.371+01:00\">4.23pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Some reaction to the changes in Irish budget from Twitter:</p> <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/Redhead666/statuses/390131227791220736\"> <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>Booze and fags up , moral down <a href=\"https://twitter.com/search?q=%23budget2014&amp;src=hash\">#budget2014</a></p>— Noreen Coleman (@Redhead666) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/Redhead666/statuses/390131227791220736\">October 15, 2013</a></blockquote> </figure> <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/CultOfCanucks83/statuses/390128138732048384\"> <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>What a fucking joke. Prescription Charges for FREE medical care started at 50c per item, then 1.50 per, now 2.50 per <a href=\"https://twitter.com/search?q=%23Budget2014&amp;src=hash\">#Budget2014</a> <a href=\"https://twitter.com/search?q=%23Wrong&amp;src=hash\">#Wrong</a></p>— Chris Hardiman (@CultOfCanucks83) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/CultOfCanucks83/statuses/390128138732048384\">October 15, 2013</a></blockquote> </figure> <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/CGoggins/statuses/390131652128542720\"> <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p><a href=\"https://twitter.com/InnaMood\">@InnaMood</a> <a href=\"https://twitter.com/graemewearden\">@graemewearden</a> Irish Budget 2014. With a million empty units on ghost estates why are they building MORE? <a href=\"https://twitter.com/search?q=%23bentgovernment&amp;src=hash\">#bentgovernment</a>.</p>— Ciaran Goggins (@CGoggins) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/CGoggins/statuses/390131652128542720\">October 15, 2013</a></blockquote> </figure> <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/fionakenny1/statuses/390131990160080897\"> <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p><a href=\"https://twitter.com/search?q=%23budget2014&amp;src=hash\">#budget2014</a> With no increase in petrol prices people are free to travel the country panic buying wine</p>— Fiona Kenny (@fionakenny1) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/fionakenny1/statuses/390131990160080897\">October 15, 2013</a></blockquote> </figure> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-525d5648e4b0a5788cef079d\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-15T16:16:32.004+01:00\">4.16pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>On RTE, <strong>Brendan Keenan</strong> of the&nbsp;Irish Independent explained that increasing the duty on beer (10c), cigarettes (10c) and wine (50c); and the €150m/year bank levy, will provide a decent chunk of the revenue increases for 2014.</p> <p>On the savings side, it includes a €700m cut in the cost of paying&nbsp;public sector workers, <strong>Keenan</strong> flagged up, following layoffs since the crisis began.</p> <p>The cut to maternity pay is also proving unpopular.</p> </div> <p class=\"block-time updated-time\">Updated <time datetime=\"2013-10-15T16:17:03.250+01:00\">at 4.17pm BST</time></p> </div> <div id=\"block-525d579be4b0081898d6decf\" class=\"block is-key-event\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-15T16:05:08.261+01:00\">4.05pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <h2 class=\"block-title\">Irish budget: the changes</h2> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p><a href=\"http://www.independent.ie/business/budget/budget-2014-list-of-items-affectedso-far-as-of-1230pm-29661477.html\"><strong>The Irish Independent</strong></a> has rounded up all the key tax and spending changes in today's Budget, along with measures that weren't touched:</p> <h2><strong>SOCIAL WELFARE</strong></h2> <p>Bereavement grant of €850 to families of dead people scrapped</p> <p>OAP telephone allowance of €9.50 a month scrapped</p> <p>Reduced dole payment for unemployed people under 26</p> <p>Maternity benefit higher rate to be cut from €262 to 230 a week</p> <p>Phasing out of mortgage interest supplement for new applicants</p> <p>Technical changes to the invalidity pension</p> <p>Clawback from insurance companies on compensation payments</p> <p>Rent Supplement minimum contribution to be increased</p> <p>Child benefit for third and subsequent child down €10, as announced</p> <p>Mortgage Interest Relief to be phased out</p> <p>RTE subsidy for OAP TV licences to be reduced by €5m from €59m to €54m</p> <p>Normal dole payment safe</p> <p>Pension safe</p> <p>Free Travel safe</p> <p>Half rate carers allowance safe</p> <p>Respite Care grant safe</p> <h2><strong>HEALTH</strong></h2> <p>35,000 over 70s to go from medical card to GP only card</p> <p>Income thresholds on medical cards for over 70s also to be tightened</p> <p>GP only medical card for all children under 5</p> <p>Prescription charges to go up by €1</p> <p>Cuts to hospital services</p> <h2><strong>DUTY CHANGES</strong></h2> <p>Wine to go up by 50c</p> <p>Pint, spirits and cigarettes to go up by 10c</p> <p>Cigarette sellers charge to go up 10 fold</p> <p>No excise duty on petrol and diesel expected</p> <h2><strong>EDUCATION</strong></h2> <p>Ending double payments in training schemes, where participants get two benefits</p> <p>College registration fees to go up by €250, as announced</p> <p>Pupil-Teacher-Ratio safe</p> <p>Private schools subsidy safe</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-525d5233e4b0570375570eae\" class=\"block is-key-event\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-15T15:50:38.727+01:00\">3.50pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <h2 class=\"block-title\">Key points from Brendan Howlin</h2> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>As rumoured,<strong>&nbsp;Brendan Howlin </strong>has announced that the Irish government will offer free GP care for all under 5s in Ireland.</p> <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/drivetimerte/statuses/390121955707207680\"> <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>Brendan Howlin announced €37 million to begin the roll-out of free GP care for the under-5s. Still promising free GP care for all <a href=\"https://twitter.com/search?q=%23Budget14&amp;src=hash\">#Budget14</a></p>— Drivetime RTE (@drivetimerte) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/drivetimerte/statuses/390121955707207680\">October 15, 2013</a></blockquote> </figure> <p>In another bright spot, Howlin also promised&nbsp;1,250 new teachers.</p> <p>But these were rare spots as the&nbsp;minister for public affairs and reform outlined wider spending cuts to keep Ireland on track to exit its bailout.</p> <p>This included cuts to the unemployment benefit, and for those on maternity leave.</p> <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/drivetimerte/statuses/390122155259600899\"> <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>Brendan Howlin targets savings of €113 million from a review of medical cards <a href=\"https://twitter.com/search?q=%23Budget14&amp;src=hash\">#Budget14</a></p>— Drivetime RTE (@drivetimerte) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/drivetimerte/statuses/390122155259600899\">October 15, 2013</a></blockquote> </figure> <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/drivetimerte/statuses/390122844517957632\"> <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>€290 million in savings will come from the Department of Social Protection, including changes to Household Benefits, maternity, illness etc</p>— Drivetime RTE (@drivetimerte) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/drivetimerte/statuses/390122844517957632\">October 15, 2013</a></blockquote> </figure> <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/RTEplayer/statuses/390125794061594625\"> <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p><a href=\"https://twitter.com/search?q=%23Budget2014&amp;src=hash\">#Budget2014</a> <a href=\"https://twitter.com/search?q=%23jobseekersallowance&amp;src=hash\">#jobseekersallowance</a> - reduced rate of €144 will apply from 25 Jan 2014 <a href=\"https://twitter.com/rte\">@rte</a> <a href=\"https://twitter.com/search?q=%23rtebudget&amp;src=hash\">#rtebudget</a> <a href=\"http://t.co/cm4cGJVgTn\">pic.twitter.com/cm4cGJVgTn</a></p>— RTE Player (@RTEplayer) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/RTEplayer/statuses/390125794061594625\">October 15, 2013</a></blockquote> </figure> <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/dec_meehan/statuses/390126559459151873\"> <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>Another increase in college fees is unacceptable - another €250! Call a spade a spade - very few avail of free fees! <a href=\"https://twitter.com/search?q=%23budget2014&amp;src=hash\">#budget2014</a></p>— Declan Meehan (@dec_meehan) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/dec_meehan/statuses/390126559459151873\">October 15, 2013</a></blockquote> </figure> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-525d5126e4b0081898d6decb\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-15T15:32:15.670+01:00\">3.32pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Economist Megan Greene isn't convinced that Ireland can hit 2% GDP growth in 2014, as <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/business/2013/oct/15/us-debt-ceiling-deal-hopes-push-markets-higher-live#block-525d49dfe4b0570375570ea8\">Michael Noonan predicted</a>:</p> <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/economistmeg/statuses/390121505340014592\"> <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>While we're at it I'd like a pet unicorn MT <a href=\"https://twitter.com/gavreilly\">@gavreilly</a>: Noonan confirms economic growth projection of 2.0% GDP next year</p>— Megan Greene (@economistmeg) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/economistmeg/statuses/390121505340014592\">October 15, 2013</a></blockquote> </figure> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-525d5115e4b0081898d6deca\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-15T15:28:51.589+01:00\">3.28pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p><a href=\"http://budget.gov.ie/Budgets/2014/2014.aspx\"><strong>Full details of the Irish budget are online here</strong></a>.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-525d4f28e4b0081898d6dec9\" class=\"block is-summary\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-15T15:26:24.672+01:00\">3.26pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <h2 class=\"block-title\">Irish budget - the key points</h2> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"gu-fc-1a2a9f7b-2853-48df-8cc0-6a444b7d04b0\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/10/15/1381847067655/008d122f-1b44-461f-b741-f1c02f7c8d3d-460x381.jpeg\" alt=\"Minister for Finance Michael Noonan delivers the 2014 Budget at Government Buildings, Dublin.\" width=\"460\" height=\"381\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption>Minister for Finance Michael Noonan delivers the 2014 Budget at Government Buildings, Dublin. Photograph: Brian Lawless/PA</figcaption> </figure> <h2>Our Irish correspondent, Henry McDonald, sums up the key points from the Irish Budget.</h2> <p>Michael Noonan has imposed ten cents extra on the price of a packet of cigarettes and the same figure of excise duty on pints of beer and cider. He has also decided to add an extra 50 cents on a bottle of wine.</p> <p>Noonan justified the hikes in alcohol duty with a mind to complaints from Ireland's pub, cafe and restaraunt owners by pointing out that he has frozen the 9% VAT rate in the overall hospitality sector.&nbsp;</p> <p>He stressed there would be no increase in direct taxation and no rise in the Universal Social Charge imposed during the fiscal crisis.&nbsp;</p> <p>Tax on interest gained from savings - the so called DIRT tax rate - would be increased to 41%, Noonan said.</p> <p>To signal the Fine Gael-Labour Coalition is prepared to impose some pain on the hated banking sector bailed out with billions of euro, Noonan said the banks would pay an annual levy of €150 to the exchequer per annum up to 2016.&nbsp;</p> <p>There was good news for Ireland's tourist sector and businesses experiencing growth this year such as Dublin Airport. The Finance Minister said the €3 euro tax on every flight would end in April “in the hope that airlines will open more routes into the country”.</p> <p>In a statement of defiance in the face of criticism from the German SPD, the Irish Finance Minister told the Dail there would be no change in Ireland's relatively low corporation tax rate.</p> <p>&quot;The tax rate is settled policy. We are 100% committed to the 12.5% corporation tax rate. This will not change,&quot; he assured the parliament.&nbsp;</p> <p>The SPD in coalition talks with Angela Merkel in Berlin has demanded the next future German government led by her must ask the EU to review the Republic's corporation tax rate. The Social Democrats have argued that the low rate puts Ireland at an advantage over other EU states in terms of attracting foreign direct investment.&nbsp;</p> <p>Expect a battle between Dublin and Berlin ahead if the SPD gets its way and corporation tax is on the EU agenda.</p> <p>&quot;The recovery is underway but there are still risks,&quot; Noonnan announced to the Dail in his final contribution. &quot;We are well along the recovery path.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-525d4d0ce4b0570375570eaa\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-15T15:20:39.436+01:00\">3.20pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p><strong>Back in Dublin</strong>, Labour's Minister for Public Expenditure and Reform,<strong> Brendan Howlin,</strong> is explaining the expenditure changes in the 2014 Irish budget.</p> <p>It will include €1.6bn of spending cuts, he says (out of the €2.5bn total of austerity measures)</p> <p>He defends the deep cutbacks and tax rises of the last few years, saying there was no choice.</p> <p>And he also points out that the Irish budget has come under strain since the crisis began, citing the 200,000 increase in those seeking&nbsp;jobseekers benefits.</p> <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/LorcanRK/statuses/390118865998741504\"> <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>Trading of share on Enterprise (Irish) exchange to have zero stamp duty. Nothing to do with AIB being listed on Enterprise, I'm sure..</p>— Lorcan Roche Kelly (@LorcanRK) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/LorcanRK/statuses/390118865998741504\">October 15, 2013</a></blockquote> </figure> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-525d4c4de4b0667d2b3c66b0\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-15T15:10:01.676+01:00\">3.10pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Breaking away from Dublin... over in Washington, there are signs that Republicans in the House of Representatives are <strong>rebelling</strong> against plans for a breakthrough deal on the debt ceiling and a new budget .</p> <p>My US colleagues are liveblogging it here:</p> <h2><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/oct/15/congress-debt-deal-default-shutdown-republicans-boehner\">House Republicans challenge bipartisan Senate deal to avert default – live</a></h2> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-525d4c03e4b0081898d6dec4\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-15T15:07:16.785+01:00\">3.07pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>We are well along the path to recovery, Noonan concludes, and this budget will help us finish the job.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-525d4b7be4b0081898d6dec3\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-15T15:06:48.058+01:00\">3.06pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"gu-fc-3ff23107-e9c8-412f-aedd-752ccbe690ec\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/10/15/1381845999741/156404a9-dc2a-4db4-9f34-c3bb779053fc-460x261.png\" alt=\"Michael Noonan\" width=\"460\" height=\"261\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption>Photograph: RTE</figcaption> </figure> <p>Noonan returns to the predicted primary surplus for 2014, saying it will help give the financial markets confidence in lending to Ireland.</p> <p>If a state cannot borrow at affordable rates, it cannot pay for public services, says Noonan. That's one of the key messages from the financial crisis.&nbsp;</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-525d4b52e4b0570375570ea9\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-15T15:04:39.469+01:00\">3.04pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>No tax increase on fuel or heating oil though.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-525d4aa8e4b0667d2b3c66ae\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-15T15:01:52.219+01:00\">3.01pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>The Irish government is also imposing a levy on its banking sector, to raise €150m per year between 2014 and 2016.</p> </div> <p class=\"block-time updated-time\">Updated <time datetime=\"2013-10-15T15:25:57.508+01:00\">at 3.25pm BST</time></p> </div> <div id=\"block-525d4a5ce4b0a5788cef0799\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-15T15:01:07.265+01:00\">3.01pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Noonan has raised alcohol and tobacco duties, putting 10 cents on a packet of 20 cigarettes, 10 cents on a pint of beer, and 50 cents on a bottle of wine.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-525d49dfe4b0570375570ea8\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-15T14:59:36.940+01:00\">2.59pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>On growth, the Irish government expects growth of just 0.2% this year, rising to 2% in 2014.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-525d4958e4b0570375570ea7\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-15T14:57:47.565+01:00\">2.57pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Onto the fiscal targets. Noonan said that the Irish deficit would be 7.3% this year, falling to 4.8% in 2014, and 2.9% in 2015.</p> <p>We have beaten our deficit targets to date, and a 4.8% deficit next year will also beat our targets, the finance minister explains.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-525d48d1e4b0570375570ea6\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-15T14:55:25.378+01:00\">2.55pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p><strong>On Corporation Tax,</strong> Michael Noonan says the Irish government is committed to its 12.5% corporation tax.</p> <p>He acknowledged the international concern that multinationals are using Ireland to lower their tax bills, and said he would bring in changes to the finance mill to stop Irish companies being 'stateless'.</p> <p>Ireland want to be part of the solution to this global tax challenges, not part of the problem, Noonan said.</p> <p>but....</p> <p>I want Ireland to play fair, and play to win</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-525d47f9e4b0885bd26bee71\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-15T14:51:37.028+01:00\">2.51pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Noonan also said the government will take steps to increase the housing stock in Ireland, to prevent a new housing bubble emerging.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-525d4635e4b06d1ee5711941\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-15T14:49:34.858+01:00\">2.49pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Michael Noonan wins approving noises by announcing he will extend the 9% special relief VAT rate for the hospitality sector -- the subject of a campaign.&nbsp;</p> <p>He is also cutting the air travel tax to zero - adding that he hopes Irish airlines will take advantage of this.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-525d455be4b0885bd26bee70\" class=\"block is-key-event\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-15T14:42:05.089+01:00\">2.42pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <h2 class=\"block-title\">Tight security in Dublin</h2> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"gu-fc-87bf7a90-0e3a-43b2-8657-1938b0008cf7\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/10/15/1381844499271/80da806e-f90b-4af1-ba75-9d9a57c1583c-460x276.jpeg\" alt=\"Image of Gardai in Dublin city centre on Budget Day 2014.\" width=\"460\" height=\"276\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption>Image of Gardai in Dublin city centre on Budget Day 2014. Photograph: Brendan Donnelly/Demotix/Corbis</figcaption> </figure> <p>From Dublin, Henry McDonald reports:</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>There is a security cordon with two separate crush barriers manned by&nbsp;Gardai including officers on horseback leading up the Dail this&nbsp;afternoon.</p> <p>Wedged up against the barrier nearer to the parliament is only small&nbsp;eclectic banding of anti-austerity demonstrators ranging from Sinn&nbsp;Fein to a small band of far left groups. Molesworth Street which&nbsp;includes the main Irish passport office is eerily quiet ahead of the&nbsp;budget which is now being delivered.</p> <p>Is it just a coincidence that in&nbsp;the same street the European Commission office on Dublin also has a&nbsp;brand new silver crush barrier around the front of its headquarters?</p> </blockquote> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-525d4537e4b0885bd26bee6f\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-15T14:38:32.687+01:00\">2.38pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Noonan says his budget will include 25 'pro-jobs' measures.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-525d44eee4b06d1ee5711940\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-15T14:37:45.978+01:00\">2.37pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Noonan says some people would like to see more austerity this year, but says this is not acceptable -- quoting <strong>WB Yeats</strong>:</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>Too long a sacrifice can make a stone of the heart.&nbsp;</p> </blockquote> </div> <p class=\"block-time updated-time\">Updated <time datetime=\"2013-10-15T15:19:54.349+01:00\">at 3.19pm BST</time></p> </div> <div id=\"block-525d4490e4b0885bd26bee6e\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-15T14:36:24.131+01:00\">2.36pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>The Irish government will achieve a deficit of 4.8% in 2014, and a small primary surplus (discounting the cost of servicing Ireland's debts).</p> <p>Noonan confirms that the budget will include €2.5bn of tax rises and spending cuts.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-525d446ce4b0885bd26bee6d\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-15T14:35:07.158+01:00\">2.35pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Noonan adds that the Irish economy is now on the road to recovery -- saying 300 new jobs are now being created.&nbsp;</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-525d43cfe4b0885bd26bee6c\" class=\"block is-key-event\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-15T14:32:34.969+01:00\">2.32pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <h2 class=\"block-title\">Irish budget begins</h2> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Finance minister Michael Noonan is starting to deliver the Irish budget now, blaming reckless polities from the previous government for causing the 'disaster' in Ireland.&nbsp;</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-525d43a6e4b06d1ee571193f\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-15T14:31:57.207+01:00\">2.31pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Here's the scene in the Irish parliament.&nbsp;</p> <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"gu-fc-52168646-122f-4565-be28-80eabebf05c2\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/10/15/1381843877105/23fbd580-5917-469c-b28d-c73baf8d59bb-460x262.png\" alt=\"Irish parliament, October 15 2013\" width=\"460\" height=\"262\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption>Photograph: RTE</figcaption> </figure> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-525d432ee4b06d1ee571193e\" class=\"block is-key-event\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-15T14:29:59.435+01:00\">2.29pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <h2 class=\"block-title\">Irish 2014 budget due now</h2> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Nearly time for Ireland's government to announce its budget for 2014.</p> <p><a href=\"http://www.rte.ie/live/\"><strong>You can watch it live on RTE's website</strong></a></p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-525d4180e4b06d1ee571193d\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-15T14:28:56.993+01:00\">2.28pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p><strong>Heads-up: one of the City's best fund managers is stepping down next year to launch a new fund management firm.</strong></p> <p>Neil Woodford, UK head of equities at Invesco Perpetual and one of the premier managers in the Square Mile, will leave in April.</p> <p>He said:</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>I&nbsp;leave the company on good terms and remain fully committed to my fund management responsibilities at Invesco Perpetual until my departure.</p> </blockquote> <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/TeleFinance/statuses/390105064959778816\"> <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>Neil Woodford leaving Investco Perpetual next April after 25 years. Mark Barnett will then take over as head of UK Equities</p>— Telegraph Finance (@TeleFinance) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/TeleFinance/statuses/390105064959778816\">October 15, 2013</a></blockquote> </figure> <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/BBC_Joe_Lynam/statuses/390105458201333760\"> <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>Top activist investor Neil Woodford is to leave <a href=\"https://twitter.com/InvescoInsights\">@InvescoInsights</a> next April for personal reasons. /He stymied the BAE/EADS merger last year</p>— Joe Lynam BBC Biz (@BBC_Joe_Lynam) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/BBC_Joe_Lynam/statuses/390105458201333760\">October 15, 2013</a></blockquote> </figure> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-525d403ee4b0885bd26bee6a\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-15T14:21:04.190+01:00\">2.21pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Walmart's chief executive, Mike Duke, says America's shoppers are also fretting about the US shutdown.</p> <p><a href=\"http://www.ft.com/fastft\"><strong>fastfT</strong> </a>has the quote from Duke, who was speaking at Walmart's annual meeting with USA analysts:</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>It should come as no surprise that the government shutdown is on the mind of our US customers. as you would expect that we're following this situation very closely.</p> </blockquote> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-525d3d21e4b0daf4692ecff5\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-15T14:05:38.480+01:00\">2.05pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Here's our take on the latest City investigation, into whether foreign exchange rates may have been secretly manipulated:</p> <h2><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/business/2013/oct/15/royal-bank-scotland-trader-currency\">Former Royal Bank of Scotland trader linked to currency market fixing</a></h2> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-525d3bf6e4b0daf4692ecff3\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-15T14:00:49.214+01:00\">2.00pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Annalisa Piazza of&nbsp;Newedge Strategy says <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/business/2013/oct/15/us-debt-ceiling-deal-hopes-push-markets-higher-live#block-525d3595e4b06d1ee5711939\"><strong>today's drop on the Empire State Factory index</strong></a> shows that US firms are worrying about the federal government shutdown.</p> <p>She writes:</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>Concerns about the current fiscal negotiations and shutdown of the federal government offices (and possible effects on the real economy) clearly explain the decline in sentiment over the month. That said, the survey remains consistent with the idea of moderate growth in the district, without signs of robust acceleration in activity in the near term....</p> <p>All in all, a decline in confidence is perfectly justified by the current uncertain fiscal scenario. Risks (albeit low) of a default of the US debt are partially incorporated in the current sentiment survey and we expect a technical correction to materialise once a final (or temporary) deal is found in Washington DC.</p> </blockquote> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-525d3595e4b06d1ee5711939\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-15T13:43:45.711+01:00\">1.43pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p><strong>Here's a rarity -- some economic data out of America. And it doesn't look too impressive.</strong></p> <p><strong>The New York Fed's Empire State Factory index</strong>, which monitors manufacturing conditions in the area, dropped to just +1.5 from +6.3 in September. That's means conditions improved, but at the lowest rate since May this year.</p> <p>Analysts expected a rise to +7.</p> <p>The drop was partly caused by deteriorating employment conditions (the employment sub-index slipped from 7.5 to 3.6). However, the new-orders measure picked up.</p> <p>&quot;Hard to tell what this index is telling us,&quot; says Bloomberg 's economics editor&nbsp;Michael McKee as the news flashed up. He quickly homed in on a line that firms aren't seeking new credit because they can't see the demand.</p> <p>Not a great sign, with the US shutdown now eating into economic activity.&nbsp;</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-525d3206e4b0885bd26bee61\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-15T13:26:31.328+01:00\">1.26pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Short-term US debt is rising in value in early New York trading, pushing down the interest rate on America's bonds.</p> <p><strong>15-Oct-2013 13:16 - U.S. TREASURY BILL RATES FALL ON SIGNS OF POSSIBLE U.S. FISCAL DEAL</strong></p> <p><strong>15-Oct-2013 13:19 - INTEREST RATES ON U.S. T-BILL ISSUES DUE IN OCTOBER TO NOVEMBER FALL LOWEST IN A WEEK</strong></p> <p>The yield on one-month US Treasury bills is down around 5 basis points at 0.2%. They mature around the time that America could default if it cannot reach a debt ceiling deal.</p> </div> <p class=\"block-time updated-time\">Updated <time datetime=\"2013-10-15T13:26:42.413+01:00\">at 1.26pm BST</time></p> </div> <div id=\"block-525d2f61e4b0931fa88f55bb\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-15T13:07:05.364+01:00\">1.07pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>RTE's Tony Connelly has full details of <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/business/2013/oct/15/us-debt-ceiling-deal-hopes-push-markets-higher-live#block-525d2c77e4b0885bd26bee5e\"><strong>Wolfgang Sch&auml;uble's comments on the Irish banking sector:</strong></a></p> <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/tconnellyRTE/statuses/390084821936271360\"> <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>Germany's Wolfgang Scha&uuml;ble has said the retroactive direct bank recap of Irish pillar banks would require a change in German legislation</p>— Tony Connelly (@tconnellyRTE) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/tconnellyRTE/statuses/390084821936271360\">October 15, 2013</a></blockquote> </figure> <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/tconnellyRTE/statuses/390084871454228480\"> <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>Schauble says this would be &quot;as difficult as an Irish referendum&quot;</p>— Tony Connelly (@tconnellyRTE) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/tconnellyRTE/statuses/390084871454228480\">October 15, 2013</a></blockquote> </figure> <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/tconnellyRTE/statuses/390085102921084928\"> <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>Scha&uuml;ble says there is &quot;nothing in the given [ESM] treaty&quot; which provides for the direct recap of Irish banks in a retroactive way</p>— Tony Connelly (@tconnellyRTE) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/tconnellyRTE/statuses/390085102921084928\">October 15, 2013</a></blockquote> </figure> <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/tconnellyRTE/statuses/390085615427268608\"> <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>Schauble: Ireland did what Ireland had to do. And now everything is fine. [continues]</p>— Tony Connelly (@tconnellyRTE) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/tconnellyRTE/statuses/390085615427268608\">October 15, 2013</a></blockquote> </figure> <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/tconnellyRTE/statuses/390085630484824064\"> <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>Schauble [continues]: The retroactive direct bank recapita