y isn't making it easy....</em></p> </div> <p class=\"block-time updated-time\">Updated <time datetime=\"2013-10-15T13:06:21.545+01:00\">at 1.06pm BST</time></p> </div> <div id=\"block-525d1f6ce4b0885bd26bee5c\" class=\"block is-key-event\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-15T12:50:04.269+01:00\">12.50pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <h2 class=\"block-title\">Back to Ireland's austerity budget.....</h2> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"gu-fc-5dffed43-a3b5-4928-9b0a-f7c40451c7ba\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/10/15/1381837769207/e01210d8-cb9b-4f29-b609-5d392eb16feb-460x292.jpeg\" alt=\"Darja Kozevnikova and her 7 month old daughter Daniela, make their way past a graffitied wall on St. Margaret's Road, Ballymun, Dublin.\" width=\"460\" height=\"292\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption>Darja Kozevnikova and her 7-month old daughter Daniela, make their way past a graffitied wall on St. Margaret's Road, Ballymun, Dublin, today. Photograph: Brian Lawless/PA</figcaption> </figure> <p>On his way into the last Cabinet meeting before <strong><a href=\"Back%20to%20Ireland's%20austerity%20budget.....\">today's budget</a>,</strong> Irish finance minister Michael Noonan said the adjustments to the country's finances will take the Republic out of its &quot;disastrous phase&quot; that followed the boom that went bust.&nbsp;</p> <p>Noonan said:</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>We want to position the country to exit the bailout so we can put this phase of Irish history behind us and build the economy and build the country going forward for everybody’s future.</p> </blockquote> <p>He added that the government's key aim - again with the accent on working families (the &quot;coping classes&quot;) - was to “leave people with the bulk of their take home pay”. (via <em>Henry McDonald in Dublin</em>).</p> <p>Today's budget comes three days after prime minister Enda Kenny declared that Ireland's &quot;&nbsp;economic emergency&quot; will end in December (more here:&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/oct/13/enda-kenny-ireland-bailout-exit-date\"><strong>Enda Kenny confirms December date for Ireland's bailout exit</strong></a>).</p> <p>Alan McQuaid, chief economist at Merrion Stockbrokers, commented (via Reuters):</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>Growth momentum is picking up, with a possible carry over into 2014</p> <p>Markets will probably see it as a final step towards exiting the bail-out.</p> </blockquote> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-525d2632e4b06d1ee5711937\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-15T12:45:08.406+01:00\">12.45pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Greek government debt has also strengthened in value this morning, pushing down the yield on its 10-year bills to just 8.45% this morning, down from 8.68% last night.</p> <p>That's close to the highest level since Greece restructured its debts in February 2012.</p> <p>The price of Greek bonds maturing in 2030 has hit a post-default high.</p> <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/Pawelmorski/statuses/390043753979076608\"> <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>Greek Bonds: new post-default high. <a href=\"http://t.co/yEJVVvORDC\">pic.twitter.com/yEJVVvORDC</a></p>— Paweł Morski (@Pawelmorski) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/Pawelmorski/statuses/390043753979076608\">October 15, 2013</a></blockquote> </figure> <p>This comes after Greece finance minister, Yannis Stournaras, and the ECB's Jorg Asmussen disagreed over the size of Greece's funding shortfall, and whether it needs to implement more austerity in 2014.</p> <p><a href=\"http://online.wsj.com/article/BT-CO-20131014-705689.html\"><strong>The Wall Street Journal published the full details last night</strong></a>. Here's a flavour:</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>&quot;First and foremost, [it] is important that they [Greece] will close the significant fiscal gap that is there for next year,&quot; Mr. Asmussen told reporters on his way into a meeting of euro-zone finance minister.</p> <p>Mr. Stournaras, however, flatly rejected the claim that there is a &quot;significant fiscal gap&quot; in the country's 2014 budget. &quot;In our opinion, there is no fiscal gap,&quot; he told reporters, adding that Mr. Asmussen didn't repeat this claim inside the meeting.</p> </blockquote> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-525d20e7e4b0daf4692ecfe9\" class=\"block is-summary\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-15T12:20:00.275+01:00\">12.20pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <h2 class=\"block-title\">European markets rally on US deal hopes</h2> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"gu-fc-42ab18e4-d834-499e-9177-4ab80670cfcb\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/10/15/1381835922239/1543ff23-a011-4b51-b819-f169258f22dc-460x288.jpeg\" alt=\"A foam figure of a bull, the symbol for a positive trend at stock markets, is pictured as the German share price index DAX reached a new all-time high at the stock exchange in Frankfurt, October 15, 2013.\" width=\"460\" height=\"288\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption>Feeling bullish? A foam figure of a bull at the Frankfurt stock market today. where the DAX hit a record high. Photograph: KAI PFAFFENBACH/REUTERS</figcaption> </figure> <p>It's been a good morning in Europe's stock markets, thanks to optimism that the US Congress can agree a debt ceiling increase and a budget for 2014 in time to avoid a disastrous default (<a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/business/2013/oct/15/us-debt-ceiling-deal-hopes-push-markets-higher-live#block-525cd9c9e4b0885bd26bee48\"><strong>see my opening posts for the backstory</strong></a>).</p> <p><strong>Germany's DAX index</strong> is at a new lifetime high, while the <strong>French CAC</strong> has hit levels not seen since 2008. The <strong>FTSE 100</strong> is at its highest so far this month.</p> <p>Only Italy, <a href=\"http://online.wsj.com/article/SB10001424052702303376904579135493169550488.html\"><strong>where the government is locked in discussions over its own 2014 budget</strong></a>, failed to rally.</p> <p>The relief came after Senate leaders declared last night they'd made real progress towards a deal.</p> <p><strong>Toby Morris</strong>, senior sales trader at CMC Markets, said investors were keen to get into equities before a US deal is announced. This morning's <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/business/2013/oct/15/us-debt-ceiling-deal-hopes-push-markets-higher-live#block-525d04d3e4b0885bd26bee55\"><strong>strong German&nbsp;</strong></a><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/business/2013/oct/15/us-debt-ceiling-deal-hopes-push-markets-higher-live#block-525d04d3e4b0885bd26bee55\"><strong>ZEW confidence reading</strong></a> was also cheering the City.</p> <p>Morris also pointed out that an index of small US firms hit a record high yesterday:</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>Either markets have absolute faith that politicians in the US will ultimately do the right thing, or have simply become numb to big macro shocks in the last few years, but to see the US Russell small cap index posting fresh all time high’s as a deadline dubbed “financial apocalypse” sits so close seems dangerous to say the least.</p> </blockquote> <p>Here's the latest prices in Europe:</p> <ul> <li><strong>FTSE 100: up 60 points at 6568, + 1%</strong></li> <li><strong>German DAX: up 67 points at 8791, +0.77%</strong></li> <li><strong>French CAC: up 26 points at4249, +0.6%</strong></li> <li><strong>Italian FTSE MIB: flat</strong></li> <li><strong>Spanish IBEX: up 46 points at 9743, + 0.5%</strong></li> </ul> <p>A US debt ceiling deal will, as the cliche has it, kick the can down the road. The question is, how far. Sebastien Galy of Soci&eacute;t&eacute; G&eacute;n&eacute;rale comments:&nbsp;</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>Kick it like Beckham.....</p> <p>The eternal question is whether it is his left foot or the right one. The outlines of the senate debt ceiling deal suggest such a kick down the road with the main work left to a committee (tax code..). I leave you the judge of which foot they used.</p> <p>Given the success of such committees, it is a delaying tactic suggesting a series of hard fought battles lie ahead for the incumbent administration.</p> </blockquote> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-525d19c7e4b0daf4692ecfe0\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-15T11:47:45.329+01:00\">11.47am <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>The UK government has denied that <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/business/2013/oct/15/us-debt-ceiling-deal-hopes-push-markets-higher-live#block-525d0508e4b06d1ee5711931\"><strong>this morning's increase in UK house prices to a record high</strong></a> (according to the ONS) means its new Help to Buy scheme is a mistake.</p> <p><strong>A HM Treasury spokesperson </strong>said:</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>We’re encouraged to see signs that house prices are recovering from a low base alongside the wider economy.</p> <p>However, the government understands that the housing and mortgage markets are yet to return to their long run levels, leaving too many people – especially first-time buyers – struggling to afford historically high level of deposits.</p> <p>That’s why the Help to Buy mortgage guarantee is a vital tool to give young people the same opportunity to get a foot on the property ladder as previous generations.</p> </blockquote> <p>Should also flag up an interesting blogpost on FT Alphaville by <a href=\"http://www.twitter.com/fd\">Dan McCrum</a>&nbsp;this morning, showing how London (and UK) house prices are some way below their pre-crisis peak once you adjust for inflation:</p> <h2><a href=\"http://ftalphaville.ft.com/2013/10/15/1666322/wait-what-the-enormous-unnoticed-collapse-in-london-property-prices/\">Wait what, the enormous unnoticed collapse in London property prices</a></h2> </div> <p class=\"block-time updated-time\">Updated <time datetime=\"2013-10-15T11:47:58.738+01:00\">at 11.47am BST</time></p> </div> <div id=\"block-525d147fe4b0daf4692ecfde\" class=\"block is-summary\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-15T11:20:38.758+01:00\">11.20am <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <h2 class=\"block-title\">Irish austerity budget this afternoon</h2> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>It's an important day in Ireland, where the government is preparing to announce its budget for 2014.</p> <p>The broad message is expected to be another year of spending cuts and fiscal squeeze, but there could be a few measures to help the public&nbsp;</p> <p>Ministers are already arguing that today's budget will help those trying to cope with Ireland's long austerity drive.</p> <p><strong>From Dublin, Henry McDonald sets the scene:</strong></p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>Rising star in the main party of government, Fine Gael, Brian Hayes sets the tone for today's budget by portraying it as a range of measures to help the &quot;coping classes&quot; of Ireland.</p> <p>The Junior Minister's choice of phrase echoes Ed Miliband's reference to the &quot;Squeezed middle&quot;, the middle classes and the working poor, who have continued to work and pay their taxes in the midst of the economic crash, the age of austerity and the cost of living crisis.&nbsp;</p> <p>But there will be as much as George Osborne as Ed Balls or Miliband in today's budget delivered this afternoon in the Dail by two ministers: Fine Gael's Finance Minister Michael Noonon and Labour's Minister for Public Expenditure and Reform, Brendan Howlin.&nbsp;</p> <p>In an appeal to the &quot;coping classes&quot; especially those with small children the government will announce its well flagged up plan to give free GP care to all under 5s in Ireland. This measure is seen as a major concession to the Labour Party in the Coalition and will be trumpeted as one designed to help young, working families AKA the &quot;coping classes&quot; AKA &quot;the squeezed middle.&quot;</p> <p>Noonan will reveal a range of cuts totalling €2.5bn including a hefty reduction in unemployment benefit to the jobless under the age of 25. Their jobseeker's will be slashed from the current €144 per week to €100. And the age of eligibility for the full social payment of €188 (still one of the most generous in the whole of the EU) per week will be raised to the age of 26.&nbsp;</p> <p>Prescription charges for medicines will be raised from €1.50 to €2.50. Citizens digging deep to pay for a range of medications in the Republic will be looking enviously across the border to Northern Ireland where their counterparts pay nothing for prescriptions.&nbsp;</p> <p>In what could be a political gamble given that they are the one section of the Irish population inclined to get out and vote, the Fine Gael-Labour coalition have put pressure for the first time in years on Ireland's pensioners. This interest group, normally immune from budget cuts, will experience some cost cutting measures. One in ten of all pensioners over 70 will lose their full medical card entitling them to free health care. A subsidy of €114 per year to pay pensioners' telephone bills will also be scrapped while a death grant to pay for funerals - worth €850 until today - will be abolished.&nbsp;</p> <p>Irish pensioners however will remain among the most well off OAP's anywhere in the EU because they will continue to enjoy free travel (north and south of the border), a free TV license and subsidies to their gas and electricity bills.&nbsp;</p> <p>Overall there is expected to be around €900 million raised in new taxes to reach today's budget target of savings.&nbsp;</p> </blockquote> <p><strong>Henry adds that the debate on the budget, which begins with Michael Noonan's speech to the Dail around 2.30pm, is likely to last until the early evening.&nbsp;</strong></p> </div> <p class=\"block-time updated-time\">Updated <time datetime=\"2013-10-15T11:37:24.809+01:00\">at 11.37am BST</time></p> </div> <div id=\"block-525d11b5e4b0885bd26bee58\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-15T11:09:39.495+01:00\">11.09am <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p><strong>From China, chancellor George Osborne</strong> tweets that the&nbsp;Industrial and Commercial Bank of China&nbsp;Limited will soon become the first Chinese mainland bank to sell a renminbi bond in&nbsp;the City.</p> <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/George_Osborne/statuses/390053529001664512\"> <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>ICBC will issue an RMB bond in London next month. First issued by a mainland <a href=\"https://twitter.com/search?q=%23China&amp;src=hash\">#China</a> headquartered bank.</p>— George Osborne (@George_Osborne) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/George_Osborne/statuses/390053529001664512\">October 15, 2013</a></blockquote> </figure> <p>The news comes as Osborne continues to lead a ministerial delegation to China.</p> <p>Overnight, the two countries also announced plans to allow Chinese banks to open branches in London, an agreement to allow sterling to be traded directly against the renminbi, and a&nbsp;&pound;8.2bn quote for&nbsp;UK banks to invest in Chinese securities. <a href=\"http://uk.reuters.com/article/2013/10/15/uk-china-uk-rqfii-idUKBRE99E06Y20131015\"><strong>More here</strong></a>.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-525d0b54e4b0885bd26bee57\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-15T10:57:39.016+01:00\">10.57am <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p><strong>The gold price has hit a new three month low today, shedding $18 from its early-morning high to $1,257 per ounce.</strong></p> <p>That could be people moving out of gold and into shares (Europe's markets are still up), and also reflects the US dollar rising against most currencies this morning (so you should need fewer dollars to buy a lump of gold).</p> <p><strong>Ishaq Siddiqi, market strategist at&nbsp;ETX Capital</strong>, summed up the markets:</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>&nbsp;Equities looking perky, US dollar gaining lost ground versus other currencies,&nbsp;gold&nbsp;reversing previous session gains... and bonds falling out of favour on risk-on mood currently sweeping price-action.</p> <p>US lawmakers are finally making headway on a deal to avert financial destruction before Thursday’s D-day deadline, propping up market sentiment in overnight trade across US and Asian share markets, pulling up Europe this morning.</p> </blockquote> <p>Gold's been volatile for a while, driven in part by speculation on when the Federal Reserve will ease its stimulus programme. If the progress in Washington does lead to a deal, that might help to put Fed 'tapering' back on the agenda (<em>or put another way, it's hard to see the Fed ending its money printing if the US is flirting with default</em>).</p> </div> <p class=\"block-time updated-time\">Updated <time datetime=\"2013-10-15T11:07:10.664+01:00\">at 11.07am BST</time></p> </div> <div id=\"block-525d0620e4b0885bd26bee56\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-15T10:24:08.100+01:00\">10.24am <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Around half the trades in Royal Mail so far today are small investors selling their allocation of 227 shares, according to IG's David Jones.</p> <p>He also sees signs that traders are taking the opportunity to 'short' Royal Mail -- betting that it will drop in the coming days.</p> <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/DavidJones_IG/statuses/390043210325970944\"> <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>Shorts building on Royal Mail amongst IG client accounts. Now 36% short. Rare to see this many bears on a share - but could be some hedging</p>— David Jones (@DavidJones_IG) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/DavidJones_IG/statuses/390043210325970944\">October 15, 2013</a></blockquote> </figure> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-525d04d3e4b0885bd26bee55\" class=\"block is-key-event\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-15T10:17:57.756+01:00\">10.17am <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <h2 class=\"block-title\">German economic confidence jumps</h2> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p><strong>Economic confidence in Germany has hit its highest level since April 2010, as Europe's powerhouse</strong><strong>&nbsp;remained calm in the face of US budget and debt ceiling deadlock</strong>.</p> <p>The monthly ZEW index jumped to&nbsp;52.8, much better than forecasts of 49.6.</p> <p>ZEW, the German think tank, said 'good early indicators' in the domestic and eurozone economy were had driven sentiment.</p> <p>Without the problems in the US, the reading could have been even higher, it added.</p> <p>Here's more news flashes from Reuters:</p> <p><strong>15-Oct-2013 10:11 - ZEW ECONOMIST - RECESSION IN EURO ZONE IS BOTTOMING OUT </strong></p> <p><strong>15-Oct-2013 10:12 - ZEW ECONOMIST - EURO ZONE CRISIS IS OVER, FOR THE MOMENT&nbsp;</strong></p> </div> <p class=\"block-time updated-time\">Updated <time datetime=\"2013-10-15T10:18:25.284+01:00\">at 10.18am BST</time></p> </div> <div id=\"block-525d0508e4b06d1ee5711931\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-15T10:08:42.378+01:00\">10.08am <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>In other UK economic news, <strong>house prices in the UK have hit a new record high</strong>.</p> <p>The ONS's monthly house price index increased to&nbsp;185.8, beating the previous peak set in January 2008. That means the&nbsp;average price of a house or flat in the UK is now &pound;247,000 - with London and the South East leading the way.</p> <p>Sky's Ed Conway tweets the key points:&nbsp;</p> <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/EdConwaySky/statuses/390037196540899329\"> <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>Here's the region-by-region house price inflation breakdown. Figs: ONS <a href=\"http://t.co/DwKKkjE8pi\">pic.twitter.com/DwKKkjE8pi</a></p>— Ed Conway (@EdConwaySky) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/EdConwaySky/statuses/390037196540899329\">October 15, 2013</a></blockquote> </figure> <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/EdConwaySky/statuses/390035844586668032\"> <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>UK house prices now higher than they were in 2008. Perfect time for a massive govt-funded homebuying subsidy <a href=\"http://t.co/aKFu5LtxCu\">pic.twitter.com/aKFu5LtxCu</a></p>— Ed Conway (@EdConwaySky) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/EdConwaySky/statuses/390035844586668032\">October 15, 2013</a></blockquote> </figure> <p>While Capital Economic's Matthew Pointon urges caution:</p> <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/matpointon/statuses/390034951241867265\"> <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>Don't read too much into ONS claiming prices in UK at record high - they are weighted towards higher value properties and therefore London.</p>— Matthew Pointon (@matpointon) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/matpointon/statuses/390034951241867265\">October 15, 2013</a></blockquote> </figure> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-525d0306e4b0931fa88f5590\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-15T10:02:43.828+01:00\">10.02am <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Rising education costs also helped keep UK inflation at 2.7% in September.</p> <p>The ONS reports that they rose by 21.4% compared with a year ago, the highest annual rise in education prices since records began in 1997.</p> <p><strong>Here's James Knightley of ING's take</strong>:</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>Fuel was the main dampening influence with the YoY rate for this component dropping to -1.6%. However, food price inflation rose in YoY terms while air fares also made a big upwards contribution and education costs, which were up 21.4%YoY, saw the fastest annual rise since records began.</p> </blockquote> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-525d0181e4b06d1ee571192b\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-15T09:52:22.552+01:00\">9.52am <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>This graph shows how CPI inflation has been volatile over the last decade, and hasn't hit the Bank of England's 2% target in close to four years.</p> <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"gu-fc-0fc19bde-4c8b-4ddd-9741-890a70c7f515\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/10/15/1381826944441/fd93545e-8d1d-4dc7-a802-e1d1d27fdb80-460x330.png\" alt=\"UK inflation over last decade, to September 2013\" width=\"460\" height=\"330\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption>UK inflation over last decade, to September 2013 Photograph: /ONS</figcaption> </figure> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-525cff4ee4b0931fa88f558b\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-15T09:45:12.196+01:00\">9.45am <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p><strong>The pound rose</strong> on the news that UK inflation was higher than forecast - gaining a quarter of a cent to above $1.60.</p> <p><strong>And Britain's borrowing costs have also increased. </strong>&nbsp;The yield (or interest rate) on 10-year gilts up 0.05 percentage points to 2.802%, the highest since September 25th, as the price of the bond falls.</p> <p>Traders may be anticipating that higher inflation will force the Bank of England to raise interest rates earlier than planned, and that there's even less chance of another quantitative easing (bond-buying) programme.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-525cfd07e4b0931fa88f5588\" class=\"block is-key-event\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-15T09:39:32.005+01:00\">9.39am <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <h2 class=\"block-title\">UK inflation released</h2> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p><strong>Just in - UK inflation was unchanged last month, defying expectations that the rising cost of living would ease.</strong></p> <p>The Consumer Prices index came in at 2.7% on an annual basis in September. Economists had predicted that CPI would ease to 2.6%.&nbsp;Price rose by 0.4% on a month-on-month basis, the Office for National Statistics said.</p> <p>The ONS reported that the largest upward contribution came from air fares, though this&nbsp;was offset by a downward contribution from petrol and diesel prices.</p> <p>The Retail Prices Index edged down from 3.3% to 3.2%.</p> <p>The ONS also reported that&nbsp;Food and non-alcoholic beverage prices are 4.3% higher than a year ago, while alcoholic beverages were up 5.4%.</p> <p><strong><em>More to follow....</em></strong></p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-525cfc50e4b0885bd26bee50\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-15T09:29:57.885+01:00\">9.29am <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Looking at <strong>Royal Mail</strong> again, a lot of the trades passing through the City this morning are for exactly 227 shares:</p> <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"gu-fc-33d511ff-7940-4ea0-870c-7d3149d196d9\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/10/15/1381825615077/5b35f08d-cbb8-41fd-bf90-e38279ca96b3-460x257.png\" alt=\"Royal Mail trading, 15 October 2013\" width=\"460\" height=\"257\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption>Photograph: Thomson Reuters</figcaption> </figure> <p>That's members of the public selling the shares they received last week, banking a profit of over &pound;300.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-525cfb1de4b0931fa88f5586\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-15T09:23:32.183+01:00\">9.23am <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Here's our news story on the surprise news this morning that&nbsp;<strong>Angela Ahrendts</strong>&nbsp;is leaving Burberry for a new senior role at Apple:&nbsp;</p> <h2><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/business/2013/oct/15/burberry-angela-ahrendts-new-job-apple\">Burberry chief Angela Ahrendts leaves for new job at Apple</a></h2> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-525cf542e4b0931fa88f5583\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-15T09:20:06.975+01:00\">9.20am <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>In the eurozone, European Council president <strong>Herman Van Rompuy</strong> has reportedly declared that the existential threat to the euro is &quot;behind us&quot;.</p> <p>Van Rompuy also told an audience in Cyprus that the EU will continue to stand by Cyprus as it implements its bailout programme (which has already helped push it into a steep recession).</p> <p>He's been holding a press conference with president&nbsp;<strong>Nicos Anastasiades, </strong>from where his staff have tweeted a picture:</p> <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/euHvR/statuses/390021875671506944\"> <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>Ambitious reforms in Cyprus will pay off. EU will continue to s