 this morning, even though a strike ballot is looming.</p> <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/truemagic68/statuses/389990127621386240\"> <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>Only 300 out of 800 funds were allocated shares in Royal Mail last week! So activity may be lively today regardless of threat of strike!</p>— David Buik (@truemagic68) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/truemagic68/statuses/389990127621386240\">October 15, 2013</a></blockquote> </figure> </div> <p class=\"block-time updated-time\">Updated <time datetime=\"2013-10-15T08:17:44.542+01:00\">at 8.17am BST</time></p> </div> <div id=\"block-525cea11e4b06d1ee5711921\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-15T08:09:29.076+01:00\">8.09am <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Burberry shares have opened 5.5% lower following the news that&nbsp;CEO Angela Ahrendts is leaving to join Apple.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-525ce88ee4b0885bd26bee4b\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-15T08:03:21.094+01:00\">8.03am <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Europe's stock markets are up in early trading, with the FTSE 100 gaining 42 points (or 0.6%). Burberry haven't traded yet, though.....</p> <p>Other European markets are also higher. Round-up to follow....</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-525ce3ece4b0885bd26bee4a\" class=\"block is-key-event\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-15T07:59:05.901+01:00\">7.59am <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <h2 class=\"block-title\">Angela Ahrendts quits Burberry for Apple</h2> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"gu-fc-630d0ab8-5577-4acb-a26a-059b85e02cf6\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/10/15/1381820288723/ceb0157d-d7fc-485a-bedd-1efe34dfc423-460x282.jpeg\" alt=\"Burberry CEO Angela Ahrendts and chief creative officer Christopher Bailey are seen leading a discussion at the IHT Heritage Luxury conference in London in this November 9, 2010 file photograph.\" width=\"460\" height=\"282\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption>Burberry chief executive Angela Ahrendts, and chief creative officer Christopher Bailey. Photograph: PAUL HACKETT/Reuters</figcaption> </figure> <p><strong>Big news in the City this morning</strong> -- Burberry chief executive&nbsp;<strong>Angela Ahrendts</strong> is stepping down from the fashion chain, for a new job at Apple.</p> <p><strong>Ahrendts, </strong>who has been hailed for driving's Burberry success in the eight years as chief executive, will take up a new role as Apple's&nbsp;Senior Vice President of Retail and Online Stores.</p> <p>Apple's <strong>Tim Cook</strong>&nbsp;sounds delighted:</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>She shares our values and our focus on innovation, and she places the same strong emphasis as we do on the customer experience. She has shown herself to be an extraordinary leader throughout her career and has a proven track record.</p> </blockquote> <p>It certainly looks like a great hire for Apple. It means the City is losing one of its more successful bosses, and also cuts the number of female CEOs in the FTSE 100 to just two.&nbsp;</p> <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/jackson_heather/statuses/389997888623112192\"> <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p><a href=\"https://twitter.com/graemewearden\">@graemewearden</a> Burberrys loss is Apples gain Angela Arendhts-strategic leader who creates gt performing teams-&amp; happens to be a woman..</p>— Heather Jackson (@jackson_heather) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/jackson_heather/statuses/389997888623112192\">October 15, 2013</a></blockquote> </figure> <p>Burberry are promoting chief creative offices&nbsp;<strong>Christopher Bailey</strong> to replace Ahrendts.</p> <p>Sir John Peace, Chairman of Burberry, said he has no doubt Bailey will &quot;keep Burberry on the forefront creatively, digitally and financially&quot;. <em>No pressure....</em></p> <p><strong><a href=\"http://www.apple.com/pr/library/2013/10/15Angela-Ahrendts-to-Join-Apple-as-Senior-Vice-President-of-Retail-and-Online-Stores.html\">Here's the Apple statement</a>..... and <a href=\"http://www.investegate.co.uk/burberry-group-plc--brby-/rns/board-change/201310150703074859Q/\">here's the Burberry one</a>.</strong></p> </div> <p class=\"block-time updated-time\">Updated <time datetime=\"2013-10-15T08:23:00.286+01:00\">at 8.23am BST</time></p> </div> <div id=\"block-525ce2a5e4b06d1ee5711920\" class=\"block is-key-event\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-15T07:42:47.868+01:00\">7.42am <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <h2 class=\"block-title\">Default fears get Senate leaders moving</h2> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Senate majority leader Harry Reid fuelled hopes of a deal last night when he told reporters that he and minority leader Mitch McConnell had made <a href=\"http://www.smh.com.au/business/world-business/tremendous-progress-made-on-us-debt-deal-20131015-2vjdl.html\">&quot;tremendous progress&quot;</a> towards a deal. </p> <p>My US colleague <strong>Ed Pilkington&nbsp;</strong>rounded up the state of play in Washington last night:</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>Harry Reid and Mitch McConnell, the Senate majority and minority leaders, held two lengthy meetings on Monday in an attempt to nail down terms of a possible compromise. The urgency of the talks was matched by the scale of the crisis facing them: unless an agreement is reached on raising America’s borrowing limit by midnight on Thursday, the US will begin to default on its payments, with possible global economic ramifications.</p> <p>Obama postponed a 3pm White House gathering of congressional leaders to give McConnell and Reid extra time to fine-tune a package.</p> <p>&quot;My hope is that a spirit of co-operation will move us forward over the next few hours,&quot; the president said earlier in the day, adding the ominous note that &quot;if we don't start making some real progress in the House and the Senate, and if Republicans aren't willing to set aside some of their partisan concerns in order to do what's right for the country, we stand a good chance of defaulting.&quot;</p> </blockquote> <h2>More here: <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/oct/14/senate-leaders-debt-ceiling-deal-shutdown\">Senate leaders close in on debt ceiling deal after lengthy talks on Capitol Hill</a></h2> <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"gu-fc-63e8a4d9-10e2-46bd-a301-880cb473b2af\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/10/15/1381819239499/66c8cd9c-af43-493c-aaef-7f058740f081-460x306.jpeg\" alt=\"US Senate Minority Leader, Republican Mitch McConnell (C), is surrounded by members of the news media as he walks from his office to the Senate floor, on Capitol Hill in Washington DC, USA, 14 October 2013.\" width=\"460\" height=\"306\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption>US Senate Minority Leader, Republican Mitch McConnell, is surrounded by members of the news media as he walks from his office to the Senate floor yesterday. Photograph: MICHAEL REYNOLDS/EPA</figcaption> </figure> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-525cd9c9e4b0885bd26bee48\" class=\"block is-key-event\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-15T07:34:27.875+01:00\">7.34am <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <h2 class=\"block-title\">Deal or no deal? (part 15)</h2> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"gu-fc-4fcf2fc1-6324-4475-9c87-73c65a0103b7\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/10/15/1381818913008/0fe0280f-910d-4e72-81d7-6a2b62056769-460x327.jpeg\" alt=\"The US Congress building is seen behind a parking meter in Washington, DC, October 14, 2013.\" width=\"460\" height=\"327\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption>Hopes are building that Senate leaders can get Congress moving again Photograph: MLADEN ANTONOV/AFP/Getty Images</figcaption> </figure> <p><strong>Good morning, and welcome to our rolling coverage of the latest events across the financial markets, the world economy, the eurozone and the business world.</strong></p> <p>European stock markets are expected to rise this morning, on hopes that American politicians can finally agree a deal to raise the US debt ceiling and pass a new budget for 2014.</p> <p>Last night,&nbsp;Republican and Democratic leaders in the Senate were racing to agree a compromise that would extend the US debt limit beyond the $16.7trn limit which it could hit on Thursday. Talks at the White House were postponed until today, to allow&nbsp;<strong>Harry Reid and Mitch McConnell</strong>, the Senate majority and minority leaders, more time to carve a plan.</p> <p>Although there's no guarantee of a deal, the sense of renewed urgency is likely to push shares higher in Europe.</p> <p>Here's IG's early calls:</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p><strong>Ahead of the European open we are calling the FTSE at&nbsp;6540 +33, DAX&nbsp;8762 +39, CAC&nbsp;4242 +20, IBEX&nbsp;9753 +43&nbsp;and MIB&nbsp;19006 +89</strong></p> </blockquote> <p>Asian markets have already welcomed the signs of progress, with the South Korean market up 1.2% and the Australian market gaining 1%.</p> <p>But the deadlock of the last fortnight (<em>this is <strong>day 15</strong> of the federal government shutdown</em>) has also left many analysts speculating about the long-term damage caused to America's dominant place in the financial markets. I'll round up the latest comments shortly.</p> <h2>The agenda</h2> <p><strong>Also coming up today -- the Irish government will&nbsp;announce its own budget for 2014, the seventh 'austerity budget' in a row. That comes at 4.30pm BST.</strong></p> <p>EU finance ministers are gathering for an <strong>ECOFIN</strong> meeting in Luxembourg, following yesterday's eurogroup gathering.</p> <p>We also get the latest<strong> UK inflation data</strong> at 9.30am, and the <strong>ZEW</strong> survey of German investor confidence.</p> <p>And in the City,<strong> Royal Mail shares</strong> will begin trading fully on the stock market, after two days of conditional trading in which they rocketed almost 44%, from the 330p float price to 475p last night.</p> </div> <p class=\"block-time updated-time\">Updated <time datetime=\"2013-10-15T07:36:06.995+01:00\">at 7.36am BST</time></p> </div><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/419975234|2013-10-16T18:19:28Z|c9b7357d372887423280ccd75c42a5acc4fd2a2f -->",
